<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99910937016018></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99910937016018><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=?item=699&mid=99910937016018>RE: why?</a> <a id=fs8 href=?item=699&mid=99910937016018#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=26549><span id=Scholar>mcoolidge</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>169 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Aug 29th 2:22 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.75]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I agree. Rangers (and the other dual wield classes) have a HUGE advantage when it comes to one handed weapon training. You guessed it: stick the trainer in the offhand.<br><br>Yes, I know that skill advances much slower this way. The point is, it DOES advance, and you can still be a reasonably productive member of the group while you train. Or, if you're in a known/guild group, you can either put the trainer in the mainhand, OR equip 2 trainers for fastest advancement.<br><br>I know - nothing revolutionary. But, just pointing it out to the younger Rangers out there who want to train an alternate weapon skill (which they should) after lvl 17. Just be sure to keep the 2H skills up as well; they're not as easy to train, and you'll need them later on.<br><br>Arynduil Greyleaf<br>35th Ranger of Tunare<br>EMarr<br>&nbsp;<br>Arynduil<br><br>"In a crowded Universe, when the talking turns to noise, you almost start laughing"</td></tr>
